text=:Category: SignLanguage%0a:Expansion: Same Controversy Present in Spoken Languages%0a:Author: sirisha_b%0a:Original: [[Articles.CochlearImplants|CochlearImplants]] %0a:OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.sathyas|sathyas]]%0a:Section: A%0a:Completed: 05.05.2021 - 17:52%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210506-184601-625540#%0a* [-06.05.2021 - 11:46-] || TA_audrey marked as complete%0a#foxend 210506-184601-625540#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aI think it is interesting to point out that a common thing hearing people may say to people who are deaf is "Oh, don't you want to be able to hear?  It will make your life easier." with the assumption that if we were to put hearing and deaf on a scale, hearing would always be better and cause less problems for that person.  First of all, this isn't true, especially if being deaf is what the person is familiar and comfortable with.  But that is only because we live in a world that has more hearing people and is mainly tailored for hearing people without considering the needs of those in the deaf community.%0aThe same phenomenon can be seen for speakers of other languages aside from English, or those who don't have a standardized American accent.  People who are in the majority will tell those who aren't that it is better to make the change, but they completely disregard that what seems different to them is completely normal to others.  As a society, we need to get better at accommodating to the needs of everyone and acknowledging that different is never worse when it comes to differences in language.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:Category:)%0a(:GradedBy: TA_audrey:)
